E. COLI EHEC - USA (31): (CALIFORNIA) MILITARY OUTBREAK
*******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 31 Oct 2017
Source: EpiCore Global Surveillance Project [edited]


As of 4:58 PDT, 31 Oct 2017, 330 cases have been reported with one case hospitalized as hemolytic uremic syndrome. Initial test results include positive tests for Shiga toxin. Screening continues, as well as environmental testing and food source investigation.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Global Surveillance Project
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED thanks the EpiCore Global Surveillance Project member for the comment.

This quite large outbreak is still evolving in Southern California. ProMED awaits more information regarding the serotype of EHEC involved and the vehicle for transmission. Unlike most _E. coli_ enteropaths, enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ can have an incubation period as long as 10-12 days.

Marine Corps Recruit Depot (commonly referred to as MCRD) San Diego (https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marine_Corps_Recruit_Depot_San_Diego) is a United States Marine Corps military installation in San Diego, California. It lies between San Diego Bay and Interstate 5, adjacent to San Diego International Airport and the former Naval Training Center San Diego. MCRD San Diego's main mission is the initial training of enlisted male recruits living west of the Mississippi River. Over 21 000 recruits are trained each year. The Depot also is the home to the Marine Corps' Recruiter School and Western Recruiting Region's Drill Instructors School. A map showing MCRD's location can be found at the URL above. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5417972,37979.]
